external_knowledge:
Economic giants: Countries with the highest GDP; 
Nominal GDP: GDP based on current prices;
Income decile: Population divided into ten equal groups based on income;
Access logs: Records of who accessed the dataset and when;
Golden waters of high income: Top income decile, representing the wealthiest 10% of the population;
Economic inequality: Measured by the Gini coefficient, where a higher value indicates more inequality;
New Year in 2023: Date after January 1, 2023;
Researcher: A user with the role 'researcher' who accesses the dataset for analytical purposes.

sql:
SELECT SUM(decile_1 + decile_2 + decile_3 + decile_4 + decile_5 + decile_6 + decile_7 + decile_8 + decile_9 + decile_10) AS total_population
FROM income_deciles
WHERE year = 2022;

SELECT AVG(decile_1) AS avg_lowest_income_bracket, AVG(decile_10) AS avg_highest_income_bracket
FROM income_deciles
WHERE year = 2020;

external_knowledge:
- "basking in the glow of opulence" is a metaphor for regions with high income; 
- "top income tier" refers to the top income decile (>90%) as mentioned in the column descriptions;
- "exceeding a hundred thousand" means the average population count in this decile is more than 100,000.

